============================================================
THE FRACTION Q_k > 1: EXACT ANALYSIS
============================================================

Q_k > 1 ⟺ |sin(mπk/p)| > |sin(πk/p)|
Let θ = πk/p ∈ (0, π/2) for k = 1,...,m.
Then Q_k > 1 ⟺ |sin(mθ)| > |sin(θ)|

For large m, sin(mθ) oscillates rapidly. The fraction of θ ∈ (0,π/2)
where |sin(mθ)| > |sin(θ)| converges to:
  ∫_0^{π/2} P(|sin(mθ)| > sin(θ)) dθ · (2/π)

For large m, sin(mθ) is approximately equidistributed on [-1,1]
with density 1/(π√(1-x²)). So:
  P(|sin(mθ)| > sin(θ)) = P(|X| > sin(θ)) where X ~ arcsin distr.
  = 2·(1/π)·arccos(sin(θ)) = 2·(1/π)·(π/2 - θ) = 1 - 2θ/π

Average over θ ~ Uniform(0, π/2):
  ∫_0^{π/2} (1 - 2θ/π) · (2/π) dθ = (2/π)[θ - θ²/π]_0^{π/2}
  = (2/π)(π/2 - π/4) = (2/π)(π/4) = 1/2

But we observed 1/3, not 1/2! The discrepancy is because the
equidistribution assumption breaks down: for small θ, mθ is NOT
large enough for equidistribution. The θ ≈ 0 region contributes
disproportionately because Q_k > 1 there always (Q_1 is huge).

Let me re-examine numerically, separating the contribution of
Q_1 (always > 1) from the bulk.

